\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f1 \'b7\tab}\pard \fi-360\li360\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxtb \'b7}}{\b Connect}: Connect to server via the Connection/Connect dialog. Enter your target server name (such as {\i eyalx.microsoft.com}
 or the IP address 157.55.80.224):
\par \pard \li720\widctlpar Authenticate using Connection/Bind dialog. Enter BindDN (user name) and password (no clear text\'85). Domain is used only with the Authentication identity security structure (see bind options).
\par \pard \li720\widctlpar Dn:CN=ntmarst,OU=ntmarst,OU=dbsd,O=microsoft,C=us
\par \pard \li720\widctlpar password:secret\line 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f1 \'b7\tab}\pard \fi-360\li360\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxtb \'b7}}{\b Search}: Use the Browse/Search dialog.
\par \pard \li720\widctlpar \{Find all immediate children of Microsoft Organization.\}
\par BaseDn:O=microsoft,C=us
\par Filter:objectclass=*
\par Scope: Choose ONE_LEVEL
\par 
\par \{Find all people in ntmarst\}
\par BaseDn:OU=ntmarst,O=microsoft,C=us
\par Filter:objectclass=person
\par scope: Choose SUBTREE
\par 
\par \{Find all people with initials e.s.\}
\par BaseDn:O=microsoft,C=us
\par Filter:(& (cn=e*) (sn=s*)  (objectclass=person))
\par scope: Choose "Subtree"
\par \pard \widctlpar 
\par \pard \li720\widctlpar Note: There are options that enable you to tailor the search method directly as
\par supported by ldap API set as specified in RFC 1823.
\par You can get more detailed technical information on LDAP search string in 
\par RFC 1558.
\par \pard \widctlpar 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f1 \'b7\tab}\pard \fi-360\li360\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxtb \'b7}}{\b Add}: Use the Browse/Add dialog and enter information similar to the following (depending on your Directory Service context).

\par \pard \li720\widctlpar Dn: OU=YourDept,O=microsoft,C=us
\par Attribute:ou
\par    Values:FullDeptName
\par Attribute:cn
\par    Values:YourDeptName
\par Attribute:description
\par    Values:MultiValued value list;are separated by;semicolumn
\par Attribute:objectclass
\par    Values:organizationalUnit
\par Notes: 
\par \pard \li720\widctlpar A. The standards (which in most Directory Services they are schema enforced) require that you use some common attribute types both in the Distinguished Name
 entry and in the attributes section. See RFC 1779 for more detailed discussion on distinguished names.
\par \pard \li720\widctlpar B. In order to add BER values (raw binary data), use the "insert file" button.
\par \pard \widctlpar 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f1 \'b7\tab}\pard \fi-360\li360\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxtb \'b7}}{\b Delete}: Use the Browse/Delete dialog.
\par \pard \li720\widctlpar Enter a DN and hit OK (for asynchronous operation uncheck the sync box).
\par Example dn:CN=Delete Me,OU=ntmarst,O=microsoft,C=us
\par \pard \widctlpar    
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f1 \'b7\tab}\pard \fi-360\li360\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxtb \'b7}}{\b Modify}: Use the Browse/Modify dialog.
\par \pard \li720\widctlpar 
Enter the DN of which you wish to modify its attributes. Then, enter the attribute you wish to modify, specify the operation you wish to perform, and optionally the values needed. Repeat for all attributes you wish to change. Enter run when done.
\par \pard \widctlpar 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f1 \'b7\tab}\pard \fi-360\li360\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxtb \'b7}}{\b Modify RDN}: Use Browse/ModifyRDN dialog.
\par \pard \li720\widctlpar For the old Relative Distinguished Name (RDN) enter the complete DN. For the new RDN enter just the relative path change.
\par \pard \li720\widctlpar Example:
\par Old Dn:CN=OldEntry,OU=ntmarst,O=microsoft,C=us
\par New Dn:CN=NewEntry
\par Result: CN=NewEntry,OU=ntmarst,O=microsoft,C=us
\par \pard \widctlpar 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f1 \'b7\tab}\pard \fi-360\li360\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxtb \'b7}}{\b Process Pending Requests}. Use the Browse/ProcessPending dialog
\par \pard \li720\widctlpar While you perform the operations above, you can specify whether you wish to perform synchronous or asynchronous operation. If you choose asynchronous, then the request is sent
 to the server but not committed until you process the pending request. Pending requests show up in this dialog, and can be 
\par \pard \li720\widctlpar committed (execute) or abandoned (abandon/remove). Executed requests will stay on the list until removed.
 Use the options box to specify how to process your pending request in more detail (basically the arguments to ldap_result). The null entry allows you execute generic ldap_result (get ANY pending requests), and a generic ldap_abandon call.
\par \pard \li720\widctlpar 
